    here’s why maturity days aren’t enough in cold regions
  </a>.
</p>

  <p>
    Early planting, short-maturity varieties, and realistic finish windows determine whether warm-season crops ripen reliably before frost.
  </p>

  <h2>Regional Differences Within Alberta</h2>

  <h3>Southern Alberta</h3>
  <p>
    Southern Alberta frost dates generally allow for longer heat accumulation. However, dry conditions and wind exposure can stress crops and reduce effective growth.
  </p>

  <h3>Central Alberta</h3>
  <p>
    Central regions experience moderate heat buildup with noticeable late-summer cooldown. Remaining GDD declines quickly once nights cool.
  </p>

  <h3>Northern Alberta</h3>
  <p>
    Northern Alberta frost dates compress the growing window. Long daylight hours support growth, but earlier fall frost reduces margin for long-season crops.
  </p>

  <h3>Foothills / Higher Elevations</h3>
  <p>
    Elevation effects Alberta gardening in measurable ways. Higher sites and frost pockets shorten effective seasons and increase variability year to year.
  </p>

